<h3>Motivation</h3>

<h4>Web 2.0</h4>

> The <b>Web 2.0</b> (also known as <b>Participative</b> (or <b>Participatory</b>) and <b>Social Web</b>) refers to websites that emphasize user-generated content, ease of use, participatory culture and interoperability (i.e., compatible with other products, systems, and devices) for end users.
>> <cite>[ext[wikipedia.org|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_2.0]]</cite>

<p>
  The <b>Web 2.0</b> offers little control to what those tools and websites are able to analyze and monetize:
</p>

> According to [ext[Statista|https://www.statista.com/statistics/266249/advertising-revenue-of-google/]], Google's ad revenue amounted to 150 billion US dollars in 2020.

> In 2016 the European Union passed a law, the [ext[General Data Protection Regulation (GPDR)|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Data_Protection_Regulation]] who aims to give European citizens more control over their personal data.

<h4>Web 3.0</h4>
<p>
  In 2006 [ext[Tim Berners Lee|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Berners-Lee]] the father of the web described the
  [ext[Semantic Web|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semantic_Web]] as a component of <b>Web 3.0</b>.
</p>
<p>
  [ext[Web 3.0|https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/web-1-0-web-2-0-and-web-3-0-with-their-difference/]]
  aimed at being a more autonomous, intelligent, and open Internet.
</p>
<p>
  However technologies like [ext[blockchains|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blockchain]], [ext[peer to peer|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer-to-peer]]
  and [ext[cryptography|https://101blockchains.com/blockchain-cryptography/]] opened up, refined and renewed a broader
  [ext[Web 3.0|https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/what-is-web3/]] vision.
</p>
<p>Web 3.0 characteristics</p>
<ul>
  <li>[ext[Decentralized|https://medium.com/@VitalikButerin/the-meaning-of-decentralization-a0c92b76a274]]</li>
  <li>Permissionless (No central authority, Censorship resistant)</li>
  <li>Programmable Crypto-Assets (Individuals are in control of their private key)</li>
  <li>Privacy and Confidentialty (Individuals are in control of their data)</li>
  <li>Semantic Web (Analytics)</li>
  <li>Security (Identification, Immutability, Tamper-proof)</li>
  <li>[ext[Trustless|https://preethikasireddy.medium.com/eli5-what-do-we-mean-by-blockchains-are-trustless-aa420635d5f6]]</li>
  <li>Verifiable</li>
</ul>

<h3>Landscape</h3>

<h4>[ext[IPFS|https://ipfs.io]]</h4>
<p>
  <b>IPFS with ~TiddlyWiki</b> stores its data over [ext[IPFS|https://ipfs.io#why]].
</p>
<p>
  [ext[IPFS|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Benet_(computer_scientist)]] or [ext[Inter-Planetary File System|https://ipfs.io]]
  is a permissionless open-source peer-to-peer decentralized [ext[network|https://ipfs.github.io/public-gateway-checker/]]
  who provides content distribution for storing and accessing immutable data. This [ext[infrastructure|https://blog.vastdreams.com/2021/03/08/why-do-we-need-ipfs-for-better-internet-in-the-future/]]
  let individuals store content with Security and Verifiabilty.
</p>
<p>
  The [ext[Pinning|https://docs.ipfs.io/concepts/persistence/#pinning-in-context]] mechanism introduces a data life cycle who
  could be seen as a [ext[Right to be forgotten|https://gdpr.eu/right-to-be-forgotten/]] implementation.
</p>
<ul>
   <li>A pinned content is kept and protected</li>
   <li>An unpinned content could be garbage collected and removed</li>
</ul>
<p>
  Once the content is spreaded and pinned over multiple IPFS nodes, data turns out to be more censorship resistant, resilient
  and available.
</p>

